


Gcost(2G)            GRASS Reference Manual             Gcost(2G)



NAME
      Gcost - Generate a cumulative cost map

SYNOPSIS
     Gcost
          newmap oldmap E,N [E,N] ...

     Gcost
          newmap oldmap

     Gcost
          output=newmap input=oldmap coor=E,N [coor=E,N] ...

DESCRIPTION
     Gcost evaluates an existing cost surface with respect to
     starting locations in grid coordinates.  Each cell of the
     cost surface will contain a value which represents the cost
     of traversing that grid cell.  The output result will
     contain the lowest total cost of traversing the space
     between any of the starting locations and each of the grid
     cells in the current window.  (Diagonal costs are multiplied
     by a factor that depends on the dimensions of the grid
     cell.) Consider the following example:

     Input:                            Output:
        COST SURFACE                      CUMULATIVE COST SURFACE
      . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
      . 2 . 2 . 1 . 1 . 5 . 5 . 5 .     . 22. 20. 18. 17. 19. 17. 16.
      . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
      . 2 . 2 . 8 . 8 . 5 . 2 . 1 .     . 22. 21. 26. 22. 16. 12. 11.
      . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
      . 7 . 1 . 1 . 8 . 2 . 2 . 2 .     . 26. 19. 18. 19. 11. 10. 11.
      . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
      . 8 . 7 . 8 . 8 . 7 . 5 . 5 .     . 28. 20. 18. 17. 13. 8 . 10.
      . . . . . . . . . . _____ . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
      . 8 . 8 . 1 . 1 . 5 | 3 | 9 .     . 22. 18. 10. 9 . 8 . 0 . 12.
      . . . . . . . . . . |___| . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .
      . 8 . 1 . 1 . 2 . 5 . 3 . 9 .     . 19. 11. 10. 11. 10. 6 . 16.
      . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .     . . . . . . . . . . . . . . .

     The user-provided starting location in the above example is
     the boxed 3 in the left-hand map.   The costs in the output
     represent the total cost of moving from each box to one or
     more (in this case there is only one) starting location(s).
     This output map can be viewed as an elevation model where
     the starting location(s) is/are the lowest point(s).  The
     Gdrain program can now be used to trace the least-cost path
     in this model between any given grid cell and the Gcost
     starting location(s).  The two programs, when used together,
     generate least-cost paths or corridors between any two
     locations.




GRASS 3.2                U.S. Army CERL                         1






Gcost(2G)            GRASS Reference Manual             Gcost(2G)



OPTIONS
     Gcost can be run with two different methods of identifying
     the starting point(s).  One or more points can be provided
     on the command line.  In lieu of command line coordinates, a
     map of starting point (e.g., start_pt_map) may already
     exist.  Primarily filled with zeros, this map contains non-
     zero values at the starting grid cell(s).  To submit the
     start_pt_map, set output=start_pt_map.  Beware: doing this
     will overwrite start_pt_map  with the results of the
     calculations.  If start_pt_map does exist and points are
     also given on the command line, the start_pt_map is ignored
     and the coordinates are used instead.  The input options are
     as follows:

     input=mapname
          Name of cell map containing grid cell cost information.

     output=mapname
          Name of cell map to contain results.  Also can be used
          as the map of the input starting points.  If so used,
          the input starting point map will be overwritten by the
          output.

     coor=E,N
          These are the map E and N grid coordinates of a
          starting point.  This option can be repeated for as
          many points as desired.

BUGS
     If you submit the starting point map on the command line by
     typing:
     output=start_pt_map
     the starting point map will be overwritten by the calculated
     output.  It is wise to copy (use the GRASS copy tool) the
     starting points map to another name before submission in
     Gcost; otherwise it will disappear.

SEE ALSO
     copy[1], Gdrain[2G]

AUTHOR
     Antony Awaida, Intelligent Engineering Systems Laboratory,
     M.I.T.












